Answer 1.1, Baseline (4p)¶

  • Dense network, at least 3 layers, shaped like a pyramid
    • Last layer: 10 nodes, sigmoid.
    • Loss: categorical cross-entropy. Metric: accuracy
  • No preprocessing, regularization. Get at least 70% accuracy.
  • Explain design decisions. Discuss performance.
    • Does it overfit (large/growing gap between loss and val_loss)?
For the first layer, 128 nodes were used, because with more nodes, the model would overfit and with less nodes, not all information was captured. Then the depth is set to 3 hidden layers, where the 2nd and 3rd layer converge the net to make a good prediction. The model seems to not overfit a lot and thus its performance is adequate. Softmax was used because it outputs probabilities and is thus a multiclass sigmoid.  (length: 420)

def build_model_1_1():
  network = models.Sequential()
  network.add(layers.Reshape((3072,), input_shape=(32,32,3)))
  network.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'))
  network.add(layers.Dense(48, activation='relu'))
  network.add(layers.Dense(32, activation='relu'))
  network.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
  network.compile(optimizer='rmsprop', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
  return network

Answer 1.2, Preprocess (2p)¶

  • Convert images to greyscale, other preprocessing optional.
    • Input shape should be (32,32,1)
  • Explain design decisions. Is it better? Why (not)?
    • Color information is likely not so useful for classification. Greyscale makes the network smaller, less parameters to learn, less likely to overfit.
Model_1_2 performs better, because now it is not interferred by the colors and thus only uses the shapes to predict.  (length: 118)

Answer 1.3, Tune (4p)¶

  • Regularize the model. What works best?
    • Should consider batch normalization, dropout, l1/l2 regularization (or Nesterov)
  • Tune other hyperparameters (e.g. learning rate, batch size,...) as you see fit.
    • At least consider tuning learning rate, ideally also momentum, decay, other optimizers
  • Explain your findings and final design decisions. Discuss the results.
    • Should be better, at least it shouldn't overfit
The batch_size was changed to 64 to increase performance, smaller and greater batch_sizes did not help. Batch normalization was used to normalize the data, which allows for deeper networks. Dropout was tested both with a fixed dropout rate and a ascending one, both did not work well, because the model is already barely overfitting. Weight regularization was also tried, but did not seem to work with different parameters  (length: 424)

def build_model_1_3():
  network = models.Sequential()
  network.add(layers.Reshape((1024,), input_shape=(32,32,1)))
  network.add(layers.Dense(128, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001), activation='relu'))
  #network.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'))

  #network.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))

  #network.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))

  return network

Answer 2.1, ConvNet (7p)¶

  • Build a sequential ConvNet, get at least 90% accuracy.
    • Conv2D layers, input shape (32,32,1)
    • Consider using blocks of Conv2D layers with maxpooling in between
    • Use zero-padding in Conv2D layers because the images are small
    • At least one dense hidden layer and dense output layer (sigmoid)
    • Consider adding batch normalization, dropout
    • Consider small dropout rates in beginning, larger dropout rates later in network
    • Consider other optimizers and tuning learning rate, momentum,...
  • Explain what you did and why (800 chars). Is it working well?
    • Should be quite elaborate and sensible
The first layer is initialized with 128 filters, to capture enough information. 2 blocks of 2 cov layers are used for optimal performance. This design is inspired by the VGG model. Each layer uses 4 x 4 layers, just small enough to push the depth and great enough to capture notions of up down left right. Increasing dropout is used to regularize and prevent the model from overfitting. Batch normalization is used to enable deeper models. The batch size is set to 64, this seems to close the gap between validation and normal accuracy more than with batch size 32  (length: 566)

def build_model_2_1():
  model = models.Sequential()
  #model.add(layers.Reshape((1024,), input_shape=(32,32,1)))
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (4, 4), activation='relu', input_shape=(32,32,1)))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (4, 4), activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(256, (4, 4), activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(256, (4, 4), activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
  model.add(layers.Flatten())
  model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.4))
  model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
  model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

Answer 2.2, Data Augmentation (3p)¶

  • Augment the preprocessed training data.
    • Use small variations (small shifts up-down, left-right) of flips becasue the images are small
    • Large shifts and rotations distort the image too much
  • Explain what you did and why. Discuss the performance of the model.
The images are of low resolution and thus the data should not be augmented heavily, because otherwise too much info is lost. Initially, the pictures were augmented heavily, but this resulted in low performance. Now, the images are augmented ligthly and the model barely overfits after many epochs, which enables many runs over the data. This will benefit its performance.  (length: 373)

Answer 3.1, Misclassifications (2p)¶

  • Report the test score (on the held-out test data)
    • Should be similar to score of previous model
  • Plot confusion matrix, discuss which classes are often confused.
    • class 1 and 2 are most often confused
  • Visualize the misclassifications in more depth by focusing on a single class
  • Analyse which kinds of mistakes are made for that class.
    • Should contain some insight (e.g. misclassifications when the numbers are curly or noisy)
In the confusion matrix it can be seen that 1, 2, 3, 6 and 7 are often predicted as a 0. Additionally, 6 is often predicted as 1 and vice versa. When we focus on misclassifications of 3, we can see that there are multiple reasons for misclassification. Often the low resolution makes it hard for the model to predict the image correctly. On top of that low contrast make it harder to classify the correct class. Furthermore, the classifier seems to have problems with some pictures where there are multiple digits.  (length: 516)

def plot_3_3():
  K.clear_session()

  model = tf.keras.models.load_model(os.path.join(base_dir,'model_2_2.h5'))
  model.summary()

  image_index = 0

  y_pred = model.predict(X_test_g)
  img_tensor = X_test_g[image_index]
  img_tensor = np.expand_dims(img_tensor, axis=0)

  last_conv_layer = model.get_layer('conv2d_7')

  model_output_2 = model.output[:, image_index]

  #new way
  with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
    last_conv_layer = model.get_layer('conv2d_7')
    iterate = tf.keras.models.Model([model.inputs], [model.output, last_conv_layer.output])
    model_out, last_conv_layer = iterate(img_tensor)
    class_out = model_out[:, np.argmax(model_out[0])]
    grads = tape.gradient(class_out, last_conv_layer)
    pooled_grads = K.mean(grads, axis=(0, 1, 2))
  
  heatmap = tf.reduce_mean(tf.multiply(pooled_grads, last_conv_layer), axis=-1)

  #old version
  #tf.compat.v1.disable_eager_execution()
  #grads = K.gradients(model_output_2, last_conv_layer.output)[0]
  #pooled_grads = K.mean(grads, axis=(0, 1, 2))
  #iterate = K.function([model.input], [pooled_grads, last_conv_layer.output[0]])
  #pooled_grads_value, conv_layer_output_value = iterate([img_tensor])
  

  #for i in range(256):
  #  conv_layer_output_value[:, :, i] *= pooled_grads_value[i]
  
  #heatmap = np.mean(conv_layer_output_value, axis=-1)

  heatmap = np.maximum(heatmap, 0)
  heatmap /= np.max(heatmap)
  heatmap = heatmap.reshape((7, 7))

  #image layover
  fig = plt.figure(frameon=False)
  img_tensor = np.squeeze(img_tensor)
  heatmap = cv2.resize(heatmap, (img_tensor.shape[1], img_tensor.shape[0]))
  im1 = plt.imshow(heatmap, cmap=plt.cm.viridis, alpha=.9,interpolation='bilinear')
  im2 = plt.imshow(img_tensor, cmap="gray", alpha=.5)
  plt.show()

Answer 4.1, Fast feature extraction (5p)¶

  • Import the VGG16 model, pretrained on ImageNet
  • Freeze convolutional base, adds a dense layer
  • Consider unfreezing the last few convolutional layers and evaluate whether that works better
    • Check if they do. It is very likely to help.
  • Discuss the observed performance
    • Should get around 80% accuracy
Initially the full convolutional base was frozen, this resulted in a less than adequate performance Then by playing with the how many layers to freeze, the best performance is found It is found that unfreezing the last block has an accuracy of 70. Then it is found that unfreezing the last 2 blocks has an accuracy of 90. When unfreezing more blocks, the performance does not increase.  (length: 387)

def build_model_4_1():
  #load vgg model without dense layers
  vggmodel = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape =(32,32,3))
  #freeze layers in vgg
  for layers in (vggmodel.layers)[:11]:
    print(layers)
    layers.trainable = False
  #start adding flattening and own dense layer  
  X= vggmodel.layers[-2].output
  flatten = Flatten()(X)
  predictions = Dense(10, activation="softmax")(flatten)
  model_final = Model(input = vggmodel.input, output = predictions)
  model_final.compile(optimizer='rmsprop', loss='categorical_crossentropy',metrics=["accuracy"])
  return model_final
